    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** and **James Wood** serving as our clear offensive anchors. **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** boasts the highest efficiency score at 79.92, largely due to a favorable matchup against Arrighetti, who offers a massive boost in SP Skill (+19%) and a slow delivery that essentially guarantees premium stolen base opportunities. Similarly, **James Wood** (73.18) benefits from a high SP skill rating and a prime lead-off slot, while **Corbin Carroll** (71.54) remains a core start; his elite xwOBA metrics and favorable platoon split against King, M outweigh the moderate toughness of the matchup. **Tyler Soderstrom** also provides significant value (65.85) thanks to his #3 spot in the lineup and a favorable platoon advantage against Rocker.\n\nConversely, our benching decisions were dictated by a rigid adherence to our 40-point \"Zebras\" floor. **Vinnie Pasquantino** was the most difficult exclusion, landing at 39.32; despite his strong base projection, he was ultimately sunk by the negative platoon split against Detmers and the resulting decrease in his efficiency score. We continue to prioritize stolen base upside in our start/sit process, which kept **Brice Turang** in the lineup at 58.63 despite a moderate SP matchup. Caution is warranted for several players whose roles are currently \"Lineup Pending,\" most notably **Dalton Rushing**, **Alex Freeland**, and **Seiya Suzuki**. While **Seiya Suzuki** holds a respectable 49.86, he is facing a tough 2.89 xERA arm in Wrobleski, and we are tracking weather reports closely, as any shift in wind direction at his park could further suppress his ceiling. \n\nAcross the rest of the roster, **Mickey Moniak** presents an interesting case; while his base score is bolstered by a strong platoon edge (+14%), he faces a dual risk factor with a tough pitcher and unfavorable wind conditions. Meanwhile, **Austin Riley** remains a solid play (56.16) primarily due to his historical BvP excellence, which helps offset the defensive prowess of the opposing catcher. We are keeping a close watch on **Jose Caballero** (56.31); while his SP skill projection is favorable, his deep spot in the order (-8%) remains a drag on his overall output. We move into today\u2019s action with a focus on high-variance speed threats, looking to capitalize on the weak SP-delivery matchups identified in our model.",
